WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.444 --> 00:00:03.027
(gentle music)

2
00:00:08.490 --> 00:00:11.160
<v David>Dr. Gary is going to be leading our discussion</v>

3
00:00:11.160 --> 00:00:13.383
of musculoskeletal medicine.

4
00:00:14.550 --> 00:00:15.920
Joe is the professor and head

5
00:00:15.920 --> 00:00:17.730
in the Department of Family and Community Medicine

6
00:00:17.730 --> 00:00:21.903
at the University of Illinois College of Medicine Rockford.

7
00:00:23.400 --> 00:00:25.140
He is going to be starting today,

8
00:00:25.140 --> 00:00:28.170
looking at some common orthopedic problems.

9
00:00:28.170 --> 00:00:29.880
Good morning, Dr. Gary. Thank you for being here.

10
00:00:29.880 --> 00:00:31.080
I appreciate it.

11
00:00:31.080 --> 00:00:31.950
<v ->Thank you, David.</v>

12
00:00:31.950 --> 00:00:34.740
It's a pleasure to be here with all of you.

13
00:00:34.740 --> 00:00:36.270
We're gonna get started right away.

14
00:00:36.270 --> 00:00:37.800
I have no disclosures,

15
00:00:37.800 --> 00:00:42.210
nor will I for any of my four talks.

16
00:00:42.210 --> 00:00:43.800
We're gonna talk mostly,

17
00:00:43.800 --> 00:00:45.600
we're gonna spend the first 15 minutes

18
00:00:45.600 --> 00:00:47.000
talking about low back pain,

19
00:00:47.880 --> 00:00:51.600
imaging, the evidence for treatment,

20
00:00:51.600 --> 00:00:53.820
and then we're gonna spend the second 15 minutes

21
00:00:53.820 --> 00:00:56.883
talking about some common overuse injuries, okay?

22
00:00:57.750 --> 00:00:59.400
So as we get started,

23
00:00:59.400 --> 00:01:04.140
remember that the vast majority of low back pain

24
00:01:04.140 --> 00:01:08.220
is of a benign etiology, okay?

25
00:01:08.220 --> 00:01:13.220
And imaging thus isn't really gonna help us in that,

26
00:01:14.640 --> 00:01:17.940
which takes us to the whole process

27
00:01:17.940 --> 00:01:21.090
of when do we image individuals

28
00:01:21.090 --> 00:01:24.480
with new onset or acute low back pain?

29
00:01:24.480 --> 00:01:26.610
Well, we image them if we're concerned

30
00:01:26.610 --> 00:01:28.800
about cauda equina syndrome,

31
00:01:28.800 --> 00:01:31.650
we image them if they have progressive

32
00:01:31.650 --> 00:01:36.300
and more severe neurologic symptoms

33
00:01:36.300 --> 00:01:37.893
in the lower extremity.

34
00:01:38.880 --> 00:01:40.980
But otherwise, for individuals,

35
00:01:40.980 --> 00:01:45.300
and you're gonna see this throughout all four of my talks,

36
00:01:45.300 --> 00:01:48.630
I'm really highlighting the Choose Wisely,

37
00:01:48.630 --> 00:01:51.148
Choosing Wisely campaign,

38
00:01:51.148 --> 00:01:55.950
which David will talk more about later on in the course

39
00:01:55.950 --> 00:01:57.540
as we get into it.

40
00:01:57.540 --> 00:01:59.250
But the point is,

41
00:01:59.250 --> 00:02:02.910
how do we provide effective medical care

42
00:02:02.910 --> 00:02:06.540
in a cost-effective manner?

43
00:02:06.540 --> 00:02:10.500
And the first year of Choosing Wisely

44
00:02:10.500 --> 00:02:14.490
for the American Academy of Family Physicians,

45
00:02:14.490 --> 00:02:19.490
number one was don't get X-rays or imaging of the low back

46
00:02:21.780 --> 00:02:24.870
for low back pain within the first six weeks.

47
00:02:24.870 --> 00:02:26.820
Start treatment first.

48
00:02:26.820 --> 00:02:29.700
If treatment fails or they don't improve,

49
00:02:29.700 --> 00:02:33.423
then you can consider imaging at that point in time.

50
00:02:34.830 --> 00:02:37.710
Okay, so if we're looking for red flags,

51
00:02:37.710 --> 00:02:39.900
what are these red flags?

52
00:02:39.900 --> 00:02:43.170
And this is what we now glean from the literature.

53
00:02:43.170 --> 00:02:44.370
If I'm an individual

54
00:02:44.370 --> 00:02:48.000
and I have a history of cancer that's metastatic to bone,

55
00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:53.000
there's five of them, depending upon my sex or gender,

56
00:02:53.220 --> 00:02:55.500
that may be a little bit different,

57
00:02:55.500 --> 00:02:58.833
but it's breast, thyroid, renal, prostate, and lung.

58
00:02:59.880 --> 00:03:02.250
Then I may want to consider early imaging

59
00:03:02.250 --> 00:03:03.720
in those individuals.

60
00:03:03.720 --> 00:03:07.110
Otherwise, signs or symptoms of cauda equina syndrome.

61
00:03:07.110 --> 00:03:11.130
So urinary or fecal incontinence, urinary retention.

62
00:03:11.130 --> 00:03:16.130
If I have trauma that is significant related to age, right?

63
00:03:17.399 --> 00:03:21.210
So relatively minor trauma when I'm very young,

64
00:03:21.210 --> 00:03:24.060
or if I'm older and I have osteoporosis,

65
00:03:24.060 --> 00:03:26.410
otherwise, I really need significant trauma

66
00:03:27.420 --> 00:03:30.300
as an adolescent or adult.

67
00:03:30.300 --> 00:03:31.950
And then the other one is,

68
00:03:31.950 --> 00:03:35.250
if I've had lumbar spine surgery in the past 12 months

69
00:03:35.250 --> 00:03:39.783
and I have new severe pain, they should be imaged early on.

70
00:03:41.010 --> 00:03:43.083
Okay, so let's get to our first question.

71
00:03:44.280 --> 00:03:45.660
You have a 43-year-old male

72
00:03:45.660 --> 00:03:47.580
who is moving a dresser four days ago

73
00:03:47.580 --> 00:03:49.410
and felt pain in his low back.

74
00:03:49.410 --> 00:03:52.290
The pain persists and radiates to the left buttock.

75
00:03:52.290 --> 00:03:53.910
He was seen and had an MRI,

76
00:03:53.910 --> 00:03:57.390
which demonstrated a disc protrusion at L5S1.

77
00:03:57.390 --> 00:04:00.510
His lower extremity neurological exam is normal.

78
00:04:00.510 --> 00:04:02.430
Of the following recommendations,

79
00:04:02.430 --> 00:04:06.873
which has not been shown to be helpful for his recovery?

80
00:04:12.090 --> 00:04:14.040
Okay, let's take a look. Excellent.

81
00:04:14.040 --> 00:04:15.840
So it's corticosteroids.

82
00:04:15.840 --> 00:04:19.563
All right, we're gonna, we're gonna move quickly on this.

83
00:04:20.430 --> 00:04:23.580
You're gonna see these in exam questions,

84
00:04:23.580 --> 00:04:26.220
and you're going to, these are distractors.

85
00:04:26.220 --> 00:04:27.630
They're giving you information

86
00:04:27.630 --> 00:04:31.020
that I, otherwise, wouldn't even want to know

87
00:04:31.020 --> 00:04:34.110
because I wouldn't have gotten an MRI in this individual

88
00:04:34.110 --> 00:04:36.090
in the first place.

89
00:04:36.090 --> 00:04:39.600
So it becomes a distractor to me,

90
00:04:39.600 --> 00:04:42.030
even though they give me that information.

91
00:04:42.030 --> 00:04:45.150
Why is it a distractor and why wouldn't I have wanted

92
00:04:45.150 --> 00:04:46.770
that information in the first place?

93
00:04:46.770 --> 00:04:48.750
I didn't have a clinical scenario

94
00:04:48.750 --> 00:04:53.750
that suggested that I had a radiculopathy.

95
00:04:54.660 --> 00:04:56.693
And not having a radiculopathy,

96
00:04:56.693 --> 00:05:00.750
I know that, in general,

97
00:05:00.750 --> 00:05:04.320
and we teach this to our learners all the time,

98
00:05:04.320 --> 00:05:08.730
MRI is very good at finding abnormalities.

99
00:05:08.730 --> 00:05:11.943
And in individuals who are asymptomatic,

100
00:05:13.470 --> 00:05:16.577
the literature shows us that roughly 30,

101
00:05:16.577 --> 00:05:21.330
25, to 35% of asymptomatic individuals

102
00:05:21.330 --> 00:05:26.330
will have an abnormality of the area that I am imaging.

103
00:05:28.710 --> 00:05:30.900
I'm talking about musculoskeletal medicine.

104
00:05:30.900 --> 00:05:32.850
So if I'm looking at the shoulder,

105
00:05:32.850 --> 00:05:34.950
about 1/3 will have an abnormality,

106
00:05:34.950 --> 00:05:39.090
a rotator cuff tear, they'll have a labral tear.

107
00:05:39.090 --> 00:05:43.350
If I image the knee, they'll have a meniscal tear.

108
00:05:43.350 --> 00:05:47.790
If I image the lumbar spine or the cervical spine,

109
00:05:47.790 --> 00:05:51.210
they'll have some disc bulging, disc protrusion,

110
00:05:51.210 --> 00:05:54.030
and some are gonna have some spinal stenosis.

111
00:05:54.030 --> 00:05:56.280
All of this is asymptomatic.

112
00:05:56.280 --> 00:05:58.320
So your clinical,

113
00:05:58.320 --> 00:06:00.450
your history and your clinical exam

114
00:06:00.450 --> 00:06:05.450
must drive your MR Imaging in musculoskeletal medicine.

115
00:06:08.370 --> 00:06:10.503
Okay, so let's look,

116
00:06:11.940 --> 00:06:16.940
I'm gonna give you a a couple of pieces of information,

117
00:06:17.130 --> 00:06:21.630
and they overlap to some extent.

118
00:06:21.630 --> 00:06:25.320
So these are individual studies that we go through

119
00:06:25.320 --> 00:06:28.530
to try and glean out what is most useful

120
00:06:28.530 --> 00:06:30.480
in acute low back pain?

121
00:06:30.480 --> 00:06:31.890
And it's nonsteroidals

122
00:06:31.890 --> 00:06:34.710
and advice to remain active for individuals.

123
00:06:34.710 --> 00:06:38.370
That's what we want to utilize, okay?

124
00:06:38.370 --> 00:06:40.590
What are likely beneficial therapies?

125
00:06:40.590 --> 00:06:41.673
You see them there.

126
00:06:43.860 --> 00:06:46.290
The American College of Physicians

127
00:06:46.290 --> 00:06:48.600
did an extensive review of this,

128
00:06:48.600 --> 00:06:50.850
which was published in 2017,

129
00:06:50.850 --> 00:06:55.850
which is still really the predominant guideline for us.

130
00:06:56.610 --> 00:07:00.757
And for acute low back pain, they say,

131
00:07:00.757 --> 00:07:03.690
"Start with non-pharmacologic therapies

132
00:07:03.690 --> 00:07:06.720
of which superficial heat is the very best."

133
00:07:06.720 --> 00:07:09.810
So that you ought to remember that always.

134
00:07:09.810 --> 00:07:12.000
Acute or subacute low back pain,

135
00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:13.770
start with superficial heat.

136
00:07:13.770 --> 00:07:18.660
If that doesn't work, then you go to nonsteroidals,

137
00:07:18.660 --> 00:07:23.660
or, that is the most important word in that sentence,

138
00:07:23.880 --> 00:07:28.703
or skeletal muscle relaxants, not both, okay?

139
00:07:29.550 --> 00:07:33.810
Both just increases my side effects and causes problems

140
00:07:33.810 --> 00:07:36.723
and gives no additional analgesia to the patient.

141
00:07:38.250 --> 00:07:42.930
Again, if we go back to looking at the pool of studies

142
00:07:42.930 --> 00:07:45.030
that have been done and what's useful

143
00:07:45.030 --> 00:07:47.343
for chronic low back pain,

144
00:07:48.210 --> 00:07:50.550
and again, I would pay attention

145
00:07:50.550 --> 00:07:53.250
to the things that are bolded.

146
00:07:53.250 --> 00:07:56.490
They tend to be the most helpful.

147
00:07:56.490 --> 00:07:57.750
And particularly,

148
00:07:57.750 --> 00:08:01.533
paying attention to mindfulness-based stress reduction.

149
00:08:05.370 --> 00:08:08.820
Again, the clinical practice guideline

150
00:08:08.820 --> 00:08:13.820
comes back and tells us we start with exercise.

151
00:08:14.370 --> 00:08:17.370
Consider multidisciplinary rehab.

152
00:08:17.370 --> 00:08:18.240
What is that?

153
00:08:18.240 --> 00:08:22.680
That means I'm using typically behavioral medicine,

154
00:08:22.680 --> 00:08:27.680
physical therapy, maybe some level of pain management.

155
00:08:27.780 --> 00:08:31.440
I'm probably doing that myself as the physician,

156
00:08:31.440 --> 00:08:33.960
probably what you would be managing as well,

157
00:08:33.960 --> 00:08:35.283
that goes along with that.

158
00:08:36.270 --> 00:08:39.960
And then again, mindfulness-based stress reduction.

159
00:08:39.960 --> 00:08:43.470
If there's an inadequate response to that,

160
00:08:43.470 --> 00:08:47.733
then nonsteroidals as first line therapy.

161
00:08:48.690 --> 00:08:53.550
If that doesn't work, then either tramadol or duloxetine.

162
00:08:53.550 --> 00:08:56.190
And we're gonna talk a little bit more about duloxetine,

163
00:08:56.190 --> 00:08:58.680
the dosing, and the timeframe.

164
00:08:58.680 --> 00:09:01.260
But it's something to consider

165
00:09:01.260 --> 00:09:04.320
in terms of pain management for your patients

166
00:09:04.320 --> 00:09:07.170
with musculoskeletal disease

167
00:09:07.170 --> 00:09:10.050
and chronic musculoskeletal pain,

168
00:09:10.050 --> 00:09:11.970
think about duloxetine

169
00:09:11.970 --> 00:09:14.910
and start it earlier rather than later

170
00:09:14.910 --> 00:09:16.620
because it's gonna take some time

171
00:09:16.620 --> 00:09:19.533
to get the effect that you want.

172
00:09:20.400 --> 00:09:23.310
So if we look at our medications,

173
00:09:23.310 --> 00:09:28.310
for acute low back pain in your top left third of this pie,

174
00:09:29.760 --> 00:09:31.500
nonsteroidals are effective,

175
00:09:31.500 --> 00:09:35.490
skeletal muscle relaxants are effective,

176
00:09:35.490 --> 00:09:37.563
and tramadol is effective.

177
00:09:39.570 --> 00:09:42.570
Moving around in a counterclockwise fashion,

178
00:09:42.570 --> 00:09:44.823
I get two chronic low back pain.

179
00:09:46.080 --> 00:09:47.850
Acetaminophen is effective,

180
00:09:47.850 --> 00:09:52.143
nonsteroidals are effective, duloxetine and tramadol.

181
00:09:53.100 --> 00:09:56.430
So what do I have to do with duloxetine?

182
00:09:56.430 --> 00:09:59.640
It's clear, I've gotta get 60 milligrams a day.

183
00:09:59.640 --> 00:10:03.300
If I can't, there's no benefit at 20 or 30.

184
00:10:03.300 --> 00:10:06.420
So if you can't get to 60,

185
00:10:06.420 --> 00:10:09.330
then it's not gonna be beneficial

186
00:10:09.330 --> 00:10:10.650
in terms of pain management.

187
00:10:10.650 --> 00:10:13.920
May be beneficial in terms of mood management,

188
00:10:13.920 --> 00:10:15.180
but it's not gonna be beneficial

189
00:10:15.180 --> 00:10:16.580
in terms of pain management.

190
00:10:17.610 --> 00:10:20.880
Typically, I want them at that dose

191
00:10:20.880 --> 00:10:23.370
somewhere between two and three months,

192
00:10:23.370 --> 00:10:28.050
and then I'm really seeing an effect, an analgesic effect.

193
00:10:28.050 --> 00:10:31.080
Now we use this a lot in osteoarthritis as well

194
00:10:31.080 --> 00:10:36.080
for individuals that we can't get adequate pain management

195
00:10:36.720 --> 00:10:38.670
for those individuals.

196
00:10:38.670 --> 00:10:41.700
And then if we look at the top right third of this pie,

197
00:10:41.700 --> 00:10:44.130
what's ineffective?

198
00:10:44.130 --> 00:10:48.900
And I would just cast this into your mind,

199
00:10:48.900 --> 00:10:53.730
acetaminophen is ineffective for acute low back pain.

200
00:10:53.730 --> 00:10:56.673
So don't prescribe it for acute low back pain.

201
00:10:58.200 --> 00:11:01.290
Benzodiazepine shouldn't be used

202
00:11:01.290 --> 00:11:04.890
to treat any of the low back pain, any low back pain.

203
00:11:04.890 --> 00:11:07.350
I know you see it in the emergency department.

204
00:11:07.350 --> 00:11:10.590
I know you see it coming out of the orthopedist.

205
00:11:10.590 --> 00:11:11.790
You know, they're adding it.

206
00:11:11.790 --> 00:11:13.980
Theoretically, it makes sense.

207
00:11:13.980 --> 00:11:16.080
20 years ago, I was doing the same thing

208
00:11:16.080 --> 00:11:18.180
because, theoretically, it made sense.

209
00:11:18.180 --> 00:11:20.190
I have a lot of muscle spasm.

210
00:11:20.190 --> 00:11:24.840
Let me use sort of the best muscle relaxant,

211
00:11:24.840 --> 00:11:28.516
but just not effective, not effective.

212
00:11:28.516 --> 00:11:31.590
And corticosteroids are really ineffective.

213
00:11:31.590 --> 00:11:34.710
There is no evidence to demonstrate they're effective,

214
00:11:34.710 --> 00:11:39.150
unless I'm giving them at the site within a short timeframe

215
00:11:39.150 --> 00:11:44.150
from the onset of this inflammatory condition, okay?

216
00:11:44.400 --> 00:11:49.400
That's not typically what we see with individuals.

217
00:11:49.590 --> 00:11:54.150
So that's not an effective strategy.

218
00:11:54.150 --> 00:11:56.730
Okay, and I'm just gonna show this one slide

219
00:11:56.730 --> 00:11:57.930
to talk about opiates

220
00:11:57.930 --> 00:12:02.910
because opiates, again, are not really effective

221
00:12:02.910 --> 00:12:04.800
for chronic low back pain.

222
00:12:04.800 --> 00:12:09.800
But the number one use of opiates for analgesia is what?

223
00:12:11.880 --> 00:12:13.293
Chronic low back pain.

224
00:12:14.340 --> 00:12:17.130
And yet, they're really not effective.

225
00:12:17.130 --> 00:12:19.050
They certainly don't have,

226
00:12:19.050 --> 00:12:22.440
they don't help our patients in terms of functionality.

227
00:12:22.440 --> 00:12:26.640
Our patient with chronic low back pain, who now can't work,

228
00:12:26.640 --> 00:12:30.630
gets put on an opiate for some period of time,

229
00:12:30.630 --> 00:12:32.610
and let's say months or years,

230
00:12:32.610 --> 00:12:35.643
they still haven't returned to work, okay?

231
00:12:36.480 --> 00:12:39.540
That's what this means when we talk about

232
00:12:39.540 --> 00:12:42.150
unclear clinical significance.

233
00:12:42.150 --> 00:12:45.180
There was no drop off in the number of patient visits

234
00:12:45.180 --> 00:12:48.150
or healthcare resources that were sought out.

235
00:12:48.150 --> 00:12:51.480
There was no drop off in disability,

236
00:12:51.480 --> 00:12:56.250
or no significant return to, if we will,

237
00:12:56.250 --> 00:12:59.310
functionality or productivity.

238
00:12:59.310 --> 00:13:04.310
The VA then did a study, the Space Study,

239
00:13:04.920 --> 00:13:07.320
which looked at side effects of opiates

240
00:13:07.320 --> 00:13:09.090
in male and female veterans

241
00:13:09.090 --> 00:13:11.730
for chronic musculoskeletal pain,

242
00:13:11.730 --> 00:13:14.430
and they did nonsteroidals versus opiates.

243
00:13:14.430 --> 00:13:17.460
Nonsteroidals won, hands down.

244
00:13:17.460 --> 00:13:22.460
They were preferred among the veterans, fewer side effects,

245
00:13:23.460 --> 00:13:26.220
and less dropout.

246
00:13:26.220 --> 00:13:31.220
So we have some new evidence, if you will.

247
00:13:31.500 --> 00:13:33.120
Gabapentin is out.

248
00:13:33.120 --> 00:13:37.530
It's not beneficial in the treatment of back pain

249
00:13:37.530 --> 00:13:39.630
with or without radiculopathy.

250
00:13:39.630 --> 00:13:42.469
Topiramate might be beneficial

251
00:13:42.469 --> 00:13:45.360
for chronic non-specific low back pain.

252
00:13:45.360 --> 00:13:46.800
And then if you have somebody

253
00:13:46.800 --> 00:13:49.440
and you're referring 'em to physical therapy,

254
00:13:49.440 --> 00:13:50.940
actually writing on there,

255
00:13:50.940 --> 00:13:55.380
the McKenzie method can be helpful for these individuals

256
00:13:55.380 --> 00:13:58.770
in terms of overall health.

257
00:13:58.770 --> 00:14:00.630
When we look at what are the predictors

258
00:14:00.630 --> 00:14:05.043
of chronic low back pain, you see this,

259
00:14:06.120 --> 00:14:07.860
you can sort of think about

260
00:14:07.860 --> 00:14:11.820
how duloxetine can fit in here, right?

261
00:14:11.820 --> 00:14:15.270
Earlier, perhaps, rather than later.

262
00:14:15.270 --> 00:14:17.070
But these are your predictors

263
00:14:17.070 --> 00:14:20.040
for individuals who have an episode,

264
00:14:20.040 --> 00:14:22.230
a single episode of low back pain

265
00:14:22.230 --> 00:14:25.983
and then go on to develop chronic low back pain.

266
00:14:27.240 --> 00:14:29.430
Okay, our next question.

267
00:14:29.430 --> 00:14:34.200
You have a 3-year-old male with diabetes, an A1C of 7.4%,

268
00:14:34.200 --> 00:14:36.870
who presents with acute low back and right leg pain

269
00:14:36.870 --> 00:14:39.210
after reaching down to load the dishwasher.

270
00:14:39.210 --> 00:14:41.250
The following day, he noted right leg pain

271
00:14:41.250 --> 00:14:43.290
and dorsal foot paraesthesia.

272
00:14:43.290 --> 00:14:45.957
At presentation, he complains of worsening right leg pain

273
00:14:45.957 --> 00:14:49.350
and you find dorsi flexor weakness at two out of five,

274
00:14:49.350 --> 00:14:53.040
in addition to a positive leg raise test on the right.

275
00:14:53.040 --> 00:14:55.140
Which of the following recommendations

276
00:14:55.140 --> 00:14:59.043
is best supported by the clinical evidence?

277
00:15:04.500 --> 00:15:06.540
Excellent. Consider microdiscectomy.

278
00:15:06.540 --> 00:15:10.740
So we've already told you corticosteroids are out

279
00:15:10.740 --> 00:15:13.440
and gabapentin is out.

280
00:15:13.440 --> 00:15:17.040
And one of the first things that we talked about

281
00:15:17.040 --> 00:15:20.280
was advice to remain active for these individuals.

282
00:15:20.280 --> 00:15:25.280
So that defaults us to a place we don't normally like to go,

283
00:15:26.190 --> 00:15:30.630
surgery, but that's the best evidence answer

284
00:15:30.630 --> 00:15:32.433
to this particular question.

285
00:15:33.630 --> 00:15:34.920
And so let's talk a little bit

286
00:15:34.920 --> 00:15:37.560
about lumbar disc herniations.

287
00:15:37.560 --> 00:15:40.620
Most of these resolve, they resolve with time.

288
00:15:40.620 --> 00:15:43.260
And the question is, how do I get from point A,

289
00:15:43.260 --> 00:15:45.150
the onset of my symptoms,

290
00:15:45.150 --> 00:15:48.390
to 12 weeks later when the vast majority

291
00:15:48.390 --> 00:15:50.430
when my symptoms are gonna resolve?

292
00:15:50.430 --> 00:15:54.840
How do I get there and how do I get there most comfortably?

293
00:15:54.840 --> 00:15:59.733
And so for individuals, right, we want them to be active.

294
00:16:00.720 --> 00:16:03.000
We're not using corticosteroids.

295
00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:08.000
We might consider transforaminal epidural steroids.

296
00:16:08.250 --> 00:16:10.290
So that the injection of a steroid

297
00:16:10.290 --> 00:16:14.040
directly at the nerve root that is being affected,

298
00:16:14.040 --> 00:16:15.000
that can be helpful.

299
00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:17.370
That's just buying us time, right?

300
00:16:17.370 --> 00:16:20.340
My symptoms get better for a period of time

301
00:16:20.340 --> 00:16:24.390
so I can go on and continue and non-operative recovery

302
00:16:24.390 --> 00:16:26.703
as long as that works.

303
00:16:27.930 --> 00:16:30.210
But for other individuals, right,

304
00:16:30.210 --> 00:16:32.100
we are gonna have to look at some kind

305
00:16:32.100 --> 00:16:33.300
of surgical intervention

306
00:16:33.300 --> 00:16:36.990
because either they're having progressive symptoms

307
00:16:36.990 --> 00:16:41.820
or I can't get them relief of their symptoms, right?

308
00:16:41.820 --> 00:16:45.367
So they keep coming back and saying, "Doc, I need more.

309
00:16:45.367 --> 00:16:48.300
I need some kind of relief. I can't get any kind of relief."

310
00:16:48.300 --> 00:16:50.220
So traditionally what we think of

311
00:16:50.220 --> 00:16:52.500
is we think of these individuals

312
00:16:52.500 --> 00:16:55.740
who have these severe progressive neurological deficits

313
00:16:55.740 --> 00:16:59.670
that they would go on to have a discectomy.

314
00:16:59.670 --> 00:17:03.480
However, the sport trial really kind of changed all this

315
00:17:03.480 --> 00:17:06.660
because now with minimally invasive surgery,

316
00:17:06.660 --> 00:17:10.740
what we find is if my symptoms are so bad

317
00:17:10.740 --> 00:17:15.740
that I just can't function, I can't function well, okay,

318
00:17:18.150 --> 00:17:20.820
and I need some kind of surgical intervention.

319
00:17:20.820 --> 00:17:24.600
Performing a microdiscectomy on these individuals

320
00:17:24.600 --> 00:17:26.460
provides them great relief.

321
00:17:26.460 --> 00:17:29.580
And at two years, everybody looks the same,

322
00:17:29.580 --> 00:17:30.960
whether I had the surgery

323
00:17:30.960 --> 00:17:33.030
or whether I didn't have the surgery, overall.

324
00:17:33.030 --> 00:17:35.940
Again, because we have the ability

325
00:17:35.940 --> 00:17:39.303
to perform minimally invasive surgery.

326
00:17:40.829 --> 00:17:43.440
This is a sheet that you can print out for you

327
00:17:43.440 --> 00:17:44.520
that just gives you

328
00:17:44.520 --> 00:17:47.613
some of the evidence-based recommendations.

329
00:17:48.480 --> 00:17:52.620
And just a final word or two about lumbar spinal stenosis.

330
00:17:52.620 --> 00:17:55.230
Remember that this is the most common indication

331
00:17:55.230 --> 00:17:59.100
for spinal surgery in those over age 65.

332
00:17:59.100 --> 00:18:00.180
And these are individuals,

333
00:18:00.180 --> 00:18:02.730
who are gonna have neurogenic claudication.

334
00:18:02.730 --> 00:18:05.760
So yes, my leg pain gets worse when I walk,

335
00:18:05.760 --> 00:18:08.460
just like with vascular claudication,

336
00:18:08.460 --> 00:18:12.390
but I get better when I bend forward

337
00:18:12.390 --> 00:18:15.840
and I get better when I sit down.

338
00:18:15.840 --> 00:18:17.545
And a non-contrast MRI

339
00:18:17.545 --> 00:18:21.090
is really your diagnostic test of choice.

340
00:18:21.090 --> 00:18:23.190
Most of these individuals are gonna do fine.

341
00:18:23.190 --> 00:18:25.020
They're gonna remain stable.

342
00:18:25.020 --> 00:18:26.940
That doesn't mean they're gonna be pain-free

343
00:18:26.940 --> 00:18:29.910
or symptom-free, but they'll be stable.

344
00:18:29.910 --> 00:18:31.470
And your go-to

345
00:18:31.470 --> 00:18:34.080
when they have an exacerbation of their symptoms

346
00:18:34.080 --> 00:18:36.420
is straight back to physical therapy.

347
00:18:36.420 --> 00:18:40.830
And so they, over the course of three years or five years,

348
00:18:40.830 --> 00:18:43.800
you may have five or six courses of physical therapy,

349
00:18:43.800 --> 00:18:47.913
depending on how often they have these exacerbations.

350
00:18:48.960 --> 00:18:50.250
Okay, so let's move in

351
00:18:50.250 --> 00:18:52.590
and talk a little bit about overuse injury.

352
00:18:52.590 --> 00:18:56.100
And so we apply overuse injury

353
00:18:56.100 --> 00:19:01.100
as these repetitive motions that we undertake.

354
00:19:03.030 --> 00:19:06.420
Typically, we start something new,

355
00:19:06.420 --> 00:19:09.600
we do it with a certain amount of intensity.

356
00:19:09.600 --> 00:19:11.160
So you can think of an athlete

357
00:19:11.160 --> 00:19:13.710
doing the same thing over and over again.

358
00:19:13.710 --> 00:19:15.180
You can think about your patient

359
00:19:15.180 --> 00:19:19.500
who works in an assembly line, starting a new job,

360
00:19:19.500 --> 00:19:22.710
doing the same thing over and over again.

361
00:19:22.710 --> 00:19:26.100
And they've limited time for overall recovery

362
00:19:26.100 --> 00:19:28.290
from day-to-day.

363
00:19:28.290 --> 00:19:30.390
That is the overuse injury.

364
00:19:30.390 --> 00:19:32.220
So let's go to our next question.

365
00:19:32.220 --> 00:19:33.570
Which of the following statements

366
00:19:33.570 --> 00:19:36.900
best describes an overuse tendinopathy

367
00:19:36.900 --> 00:19:41.900
such as lateral epicondylosis or patellar tendinosis?

368
00:19:47.820 --> 00:19:52.050
Okay, excellent. So A is the correct answer.

369
00:19:52.050 --> 00:19:56.700
Eccentric contractions are recommended for therapy.

370
00:19:56.700 --> 00:19:59.640
These are non-inflammatory conditions.

371
00:19:59.640 --> 00:20:04.230
That was my hint to you, osis versus itis, right?

372
00:20:04.230 --> 00:20:06.420
Osis being more chronic,

373
00:20:06.420 --> 00:20:11.420
itis being more acute in our vocabulary.

374
00:20:12.210 --> 00:20:17.010
And so for all of these, when we look at this,

375
00:20:17.010 --> 00:20:18.330
and I give you this

376
00:20:18.330 --> 00:20:21.090
because this is really the clinical picture

377
00:20:21.090 --> 00:20:23.880
of what these overuse injuries look like.

378
00:20:23.880 --> 00:20:28.320
On the left, or on the y-axis,

379
00:20:28.320 --> 00:20:33.320
consider this a measure of microscopic injury, okay?

380
00:20:35.370 --> 00:20:38.135
As I go from zero, no microscopic injury,

381
00:20:38.135 --> 00:20:43.135
to 2.5, where I have probably macroscopic injury now.

382
00:20:44.340 --> 00:20:47.250
The individual starts an activity

383
00:20:47.250 --> 00:20:52.250
and they build and have microscopic injury to the tendon,

384
00:20:53.970 --> 00:20:58.970
the bone, whatever area that's involved.

385
00:20:59.520 --> 00:21:02.580
And this occurs over time,

386
00:21:02.580 --> 00:21:06.510
but it's at a sub pain threshold.

387
00:21:06.510 --> 00:21:09.663
So they don't feel it, but the injury is occurring.

388
00:21:10.530 --> 00:21:12.300
And over time,

389
00:21:12.300 --> 00:21:16.230
and time is anywhere from typically six to 12 weeks

390
00:21:16.230 --> 00:21:18.363
from the time they start this activity,

391
00:21:19.410 --> 00:21:24.410
then all of a sudden, you see the injury or their pain

392
00:21:26.730 --> 00:21:29.520
moves above the pain threshold.

393
00:21:29.520 --> 00:21:31.020
So they feel it.

394
00:21:31.020 --> 00:21:34.323
So they stop what they're doing for a day or so,

395
00:21:35.460 --> 00:21:38.730
the pain drops back down, but there isn't recovery.

396
00:21:38.730 --> 00:21:40.200
There's just enough recovery

397
00:21:40.200 --> 00:21:42.600
that they're below the pain threshold.

398
00:21:42.600 --> 00:21:45.030
They go back to work or they go back to their activity

399
00:21:45.030 --> 00:21:47.250
and they pop right back up again.

400
00:21:47.250 --> 00:21:48.210
Huh? What's wrong?

401
00:21:48.210 --> 00:21:50.700
Well, maybe I'll wait a couple more days,

402
00:21:50.700 --> 00:21:52.050
maybe I'll take a couple more days.

403
00:21:52.050 --> 00:21:54.120
Maybe I got a long weekend coming up,

404
00:21:54.120 --> 00:21:57.120
so now I can recover over that timeframe

405
00:21:57.120 --> 00:22:00.090
and then I go right back to work or I go back to my activity

406
00:22:00.090 --> 00:22:02.400
and my pain pops right up again

407
00:22:02.400 --> 00:22:05.970
because I haven't had really any substantial recovery.

408
00:22:05.970 --> 00:22:09.000
So that's what happens with these individuals.

409
00:22:09.000 --> 00:22:11.070
Typically, they're gonna see you

410
00:22:11.070 --> 00:22:14.010
the third time they cross this pain threshold.

411
00:22:14.010 --> 00:22:16.950
The first time, they're gonna manage it themselves.

412
00:22:16.950 --> 00:22:18.870
The second time, they're gonna manage it themselves.

413
00:22:18.870 --> 00:22:21.270
The third time, this is a problem.

414
00:22:21.270 --> 00:22:22.380
This is what they think.

415
00:22:22.380 --> 00:22:25.440
This is a problem, they're gonna come in to see you.

416
00:22:25.440 --> 00:22:29.850
And so by seeing this and understanding this,

417
00:22:29.850 --> 00:22:32.970
it helps you in getting the history from the patient

418
00:22:32.970 --> 00:22:36.480
and understanding, "I'm dealing with an overuse injury."

419
00:22:36.480 --> 00:22:39.180
In general, it's gonna take twice as long

420
00:22:39.180 --> 00:22:42.150
for them to recover from an overuse injury

421
00:22:42.150 --> 00:22:43.920
as it will from an acute injury.

422
00:22:43.920 --> 00:22:45.720
So if we think, I break a bone,

423
00:22:45.720 --> 00:22:47.400
it takes six weeks to recover,

424
00:22:47.400 --> 00:22:48.690
I have an overuse injury,

425
00:22:48.690 --> 00:22:51.473
it's gonna take about three months to recover, okay?

426
00:22:54.070 --> 00:22:56.317
Okay, and so these,

427
00:22:56.317 --> 00:22:59.760
they just highlight and give you some of the evidence

428
00:22:59.760 --> 00:23:01.560
about eccentric strengthening

429
00:23:01.560 --> 00:23:03.663
for the chronic tendinopathies.

430
00:23:04.770 --> 00:23:07.290
Also, autologous blood injections.

431
00:23:07.290 --> 00:23:10.350
So I draw blood off your antecubital vein,

432
00:23:10.350 --> 00:23:12.750
I take it and I inject it,

433
00:23:12.750 --> 00:23:15.750
the same way I would with a corticosteroid

434
00:23:15.750 --> 00:23:17.427
for over the lateral epicondyle,

435
00:23:17.427 --> 00:23:22.427
the extensor carpi radialis brevis tendon origin,

436
00:23:23.550 --> 00:23:26.730
and you get better, okay?

437
00:23:26.730 --> 00:23:30.750
This is autologous blood is better than corticosteroids

438
00:23:30.750 --> 00:23:32.970
for tennis elbow, right?

439
00:23:32.970 --> 00:23:35.040
It's the healing factors within the blood,

440
00:23:35.040 --> 00:23:36.600
the growth factors within the blood,

441
00:23:36.600 --> 00:23:38.253
they're not concentrated.

442
00:23:39.240 --> 00:23:42.870
And we then turn around and re-inject those.

443
00:23:42.870 --> 00:23:44.373
You should be aware of that.

444
00:23:45.420 --> 00:23:49.140
Corticosteroids, this is just,

445
00:23:49.140 --> 00:23:51.000
this information is just telling you

446
00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:53.550
that corticosteroids are not curative.

447
00:23:53.550 --> 00:23:58.200
They're great analgesics, but they don't fix the problem.

448
00:23:58.200 --> 00:24:00.870
So the minute the analgesia wears off,

449
00:24:00.870 --> 00:24:02.130
the patient's coming back,

450
00:24:02.130 --> 00:24:04.413
asking for another corticosteroid injection.

451
00:24:05.340 --> 00:24:07.500
Topical nitroglycerin can be used.

452
00:24:07.500 --> 00:24:12.060
We typically use a patch, cut it into four sections,

453
00:24:12.060 --> 00:24:14.490
and then put a section of the patch

454
00:24:14.490 --> 00:24:18.870
right over the area of the tendon for tendinopathy,

455
00:24:18.870 --> 00:24:20.190
right over the area of the tendon

456
00:24:20.190 --> 00:24:23.310
that is most tender or painful.

457
00:24:23.310 --> 00:24:25.800
Side effect, headache for these individuals

458
00:24:25.800 --> 00:24:27.120
who aren't used to it.

459
00:24:27.120 --> 00:24:30.060
Quarter of a patch works better than a full patch.

460
00:24:30.060 --> 00:24:32.940
And then, certainly, can consider platelet-rich plasma

461
00:24:32.940 --> 00:24:35.520
or autologous blood in other areas

462
00:24:35.520 --> 00:24:38.790
for recalcitrant tendinopathies.

463
00:24:38.790 --> 00:24:43.320
Platelet-rich plasma, I take your blood, I spin it down,

464
00:24:43.320 --> 00:24:46.140
I get the plasma, I look for a certain,

465
00:24:46.140 --> 00:24:49.530
depending on what aspect of the plasma I want to use.

466
00:24:49.530 --> 00:24:52.710
It's concentrated with platelets and growth factors.

467
00:24:52.710 --> 00:24:55.590
I then take that and inject that back in.

468
00:24:55.590 --> 00:24:57.660
So you see more and more about that

469
00:24:57.660 --> 00:25:00.663
in terms of treatment for osteoarthritis, et cetera.

470
00:25:02.640 --> 00:25:04.486
Shoulder impingement,

471
00:25:04.486 --> 00:25:08.130
these are adults who are gonna be over age 35.

472
00:25:08.130 --> 00:25:12.180
You need to know they like to ask questions

473
00:25:12.180 --> 00:25:17.010
about some specific exams and Neer's exam and Hawkin's test,

474
00:25:17.010 --> 00:25:19.110
they like to ask questions about.

475
00:25:19.110 --> 00:25:21.630
So I just show you what these are.

476
00:25:21.630 --> 00:25:23.760
These are the positions you get the shoulder into.

477
00:25:23.760 --> 00:25:27.060
It's either painful or not painful, real simple.

478
00:25:27.060 --> 00:25:29.130
And they are suggestive of,

479
00:25:29.130 --> 00:25:32.913
or perhaps even diagnostic of shoulder impingement.

480
00:25:34.140 --> 00:25:37.590
In terms of management of shoulder impingement,

481
00:25:37.590 --> 00:25:42.590
this is primarily the supraspinatus tendon that's involved.

482
00:25:43.560 --> 00:25:46.260
But remember, this one is different.

483
00:25:46.260 --> 00:25:50.730
This would be concentric exercise, not eccentric exercise.

484
00:25:50.730 --> 00:25:54.930
So this is the one that's just a little bit different.

485
00:25:54.930 --> 00:25:57.843
I don't think you'll be asked about it, okay?

486
00:25:58.920 --> 00:26:03.920
And then there's information on sort of interesting studies

487
00:26:05.760 --> 00:26:09.510
that really demonstrate that it's the corticosteroid

488
00:26:09.510 --> 00:26:11.520
that alleviates the pain,

489
00:26:11.520 --> 00:26:15.990
but it's the exercise that resolves the condition

490
00:26:15.990 --> 00:26:18.123
that leads to the pain in the first place.

491
00:26:19.440 --> 00:26:21.810
Adhesive capsulitis, right?

492
00:26:21.810 --> 00:26:24.300
This is limited range of motion of the shoulder

493
00:26:24.300 --> 00:26:26.850
with pain at limited ranges of motion.

494
00:26:26.850 --> 00:26:28.830
Think about your Parkinson's patient

495
00:26:28.830 --> 00:26:30.840
who presents with shoulder pain.

496
00:26:30.840 --> 00:26:33.270
It'll be adhesive capsulitis.

497
00:26:33.270 --> 00:26:34.680
And what do we do?

498
00:26:34.680 --> 00:26:39.120
Really, to be honest with you, we don't do anything, okay?

499
00:26:39.120 --> 00:26:42.660
I know that I gave you the evidence that's up here.

500
00:26:42.660 --> 00:26:46.740
If we provide an intraarticular corticosteroid injection

501
00:26:46.740 --> 00:26:48.060
into the shoulder joint,

502
00:26:48.060 --> 00:26:52.140
we can help reduce pain and improve function

503
00:26:52.140 --> 00:26:53.970
for a short period of time.

504
00:26:53.970 --> 00:26:56.550
But generally, frozen shoulder's gonna last

505
00:26:56.550 --> 00:26:58.470
for two to three years.

506
00:26:58.470 --> 00:27:03.470
And I typically get it on my left side,

507
00:27:03.600 --> 00:27:04.980
that's where it starts.

508
00:27:04.980 --> 00:27:06.960
And I'm at very high risk

509
00:27:06.960 --> 00:27:09.270
of getting it on the contralateral shoulder,

510
00:27:09.270 --> 00:27:12.120
just about the time it resolves on one side,

511
00:27:12.120 --> 00:27:14.043
it's gonna pop up on the other side,

512
00:27:15.450 --> 00:27:17.220
but it generally resolves.

513
00:27:17.220 --> 00:27:18.670
It just takes time, you know?

514
00:27:20.820 --> 00:27:21.990
Okay, our next question.

515
00:27:21.990 --> 00:27:24.810
The 29-year-old female recently started a running program

516
00:27:24.810 --> 00:27:26.790
in order to assist with weight control.

517
00:27:26.790 --> 00:27:28.860
She presents with right anterior knee pain

518
00:27:28.860 --> 00:27:30.660
that started three weeks ago.

519
00:27:30.660 --> 00:27:35.580
She recalls the pain was initially noted late in her run,

520
00:27:35.580 --> 00:27:38.670
but now is bothersome at five to six blocks into her run

521
00:27:38.670 --> 00:27:40.680
and painful after the run.

522
00:27:40.680 --> 00:27:44.190
Examination demonstrates a BMI of 28.4.

523
00:27:44.190 --> 00:27:45.870
She has no joint effusion.

524
00:27:45.870 --> 00:27:48.420
She has full range of motion in the knee,

525
00:27:48.420 --> 00:27:50.472
no ligamentous laxity, but she does have pain and crepitus

526
00:27:50.472 --> 00:27:54.543
with manipulation of the patella.

527
00:27:55.410 --> 00:27:56.613
So our question,

528
00:27:57.780 --> 00:28:00.300
which of the following is the most appropriate next step

529
00:28:00.300 --> 00:28:01.323
in her management?

530
00:28:03.960 --> 00:28:08.943
Do you want a knee MRI, patellar taping,

531
00:28:10.650 --> 00:28:12.933
put her in a patellofemoral brace,

532
00:28:14.880 --> 00:28:18.956
or have her reduce her running distance

533
00:28:18.956 --> 00:28:21.003
and start physical therapy?

534
00:28:27.120 --> 00:28:28.768
Great. So you all got this.

535
00:28:28.768 --> 00:28:33.768
They all work. All of these work, okay?

536
00:28:34.020 --> 00:28:35.850
And they all have a role,

537
00:28:35.850 --> 00:28:38.940
it's just that D is your best answer

538
00:28:38.940 --> 00:28:43.940
and most consistent in terms of improvement for individuals.

539
00:28:44.370 --> 00:28:47.610
So you all have seen anterior knee pain

540
00:28:47.610 --> 00:28:49.203
or patellofemoral pain.

541
00:28:50.160 --> 00:28:52.230
If I can tell you anything about this,

542
00:28:52.230 --> 00:28:54.300
the focus is all on the hip.

543
00:28:54.300 --> 00:28:58.590
The gluteus medias, hip abductors, quadriceps,

544
00:28:58.590 --> 00:29:01.080
that's where the focus of the rehab is

545
00:29:01.080 --> 00:29:03.990
for the vast majority of these individuals.

546
00:29:03.990 --> 00:29:06.600
And as I said, all of these works.

547
00:29:06.600 --> 00:29:11.263
So patellar taping works in individuals.

548
00:29:11.263 --> 00:29:15.720
The question is, will it work in me or will it work in you?

549
00:29:15.720 --> 00:29:18.990
And bracing works particularly in runners.

550
00:29:18.990 --> 00:29:22.980
So if I have a runner, give them a patellofemoral brace,

551
00:29:22.980 --> 00:29:25.680
and you can probably let them continue to run.

552
00:29:25.680 --> 00:29:28.410
They might have to reduce their distance a bit.

553
00:29:28.410 --> 00:29:32.970
Avoid the MRI in anterior knee pain

554
00:29:32.970 --> 00:29:36.360
in a patient without a effusion or mechanical symptoms,

555
00:29:36.360 --> 00:29:40.290
unless the patient hasn't responded to appropriate rehab.

556
00:29:40.290 --> 00:29:41.913
Choosing Wisely again.

557
00:29:44.190 --> 00:29:45.960
Okay, another question.

558
00:29:45.960 --> 00:29:47.970
Which of the following is the most sensitive finding

559
00:29:47.970 --> 00:29:49.970
in patients with carpal tunnel syndrome?

560
00:29:51.600 --> 00:29:54.450
The flick sign, Tinel's test, Phalen's test,

561
00:29:54.450 --> 00:29:56.223
or hypothenar atrophy?

562
00:30:01.830 --> 00:30:02.663
Good.

563
00:30:02.663 --> 00:30:03.496
We're kind of split,

564
00:30:04.362 --> 00:30:07.001
but flick test is the most sensitive finding.

565
00:30:07.001 --> 00:30:09.420
And what is flick test?

566
00:30:09.420 --> 00:30:10.253
Patient tells you,

567
00:30:10.253 --> 00:30:14.250
"My hand is painful or numb or whatever."

568
00:30:14.250 --> 00:30:17.280
And you ask them what they do to relieve it,

569
00:30:17.280 --> 00:30:20.190
and they say, "This is what I do to relieve it."

570
00:30:20.190 --> 00:30:21.420
That is the flick sign.

571
00:30:21.420 --> 00:30:25.020
Most sensitive finding in carpal tunnel syndrome.

572
00:30:25.020 --> 00:30:26.790
Remember, median nerve entrapment,

573
00:30:26.790 --> 00:30:30.630
it is the most common peripheral nerve entrapment

574
00:30:30.630 --> 00:30:32.793
that we encounter.

575
00:30:34.560 --> 00:30:38.250
You can put individuals in wrist splints, if it's minor.

576
00:30:38.250 --> 00:30:40.380
They love to ask you the question

577
00:30:40.380 --> 00:30:45.030
about do you want to give them a prednisone pill

578
00:30:45.030 --> 00:30:48.630
or do you want to give them a corticosteroid injection?

579
00:30:48.630 --> 00:30:50.130
And the answer here, again,

580
00:30:50.130 --> 00:30:55.130
is somewhat counterintuitive to us in family medicine.

581
00:30:55.825 --> 00:30:58.200
The pill is less invasive.

582
00:30:58.200 --> 00:31:00.780
It should work as well, but it does not.

583
00:31:00.780 --> 00:31:04.330
The injection is the preferred delivery method

584
00:31:05.370 --> 00:31:07.263
for the corticosteroid.

585
00:31:09.390 --> 00:31:12.360
Okay, now you have a 41-year-old female

586
00:31:12.360 --> 00:31:16.740
who presents with medial left heel pain for five weeks.

587
00:31:16.740 --> 00:31:18.540
She describes it as burning

588
00:31:18.540 --> 00:31:21.450
and worse with weight-bearing activity or prolonged standing

589
00:31:21.450 --> 00:31:23.010
and better with rest.

590
00:31:23.010 --> 00:31:26.790
On exam, you note a normal gait, subtalar pronation,

591
00:31:26.790 --> 00:31:28.980
leading to flatfootedness,

592
00:31:28.980 --> 00:31:31.650
and no tenderness of the heel or ankle.

593
00:31:31.650 --> 00:31:32.940
Symptoms are aggravated

594
00:31:32.940 --> 00:31:36.390
by full passive dorsiflexion of the ankle.

595
00:31:36.390 --> 00:31:38.553
And you conclude which of the following?

596
00:31:40.170 --> 00:31:43.593
She has tarsal tunnel syndrome, you provide her an orthotic.

597
00:31:44.550 --> 00:31:47.733
She has a calcaneal stress fracture, you order an MRI.

598
00:31:48.870 --> 00:31:52.230
She has heel pad syndrome, you give her a heel cup.

599
00:31:52.230 --> 00:31:53.820
Or she has plantar fasciitis,

600
00:31:53.820 --> 00:31:55.820
and you provide her with a night splint.

601
00:32:00.960 --> 00:32:03.360
This individual has tarsal tunnel syndrome,

602
00:32:03.360 --> 00:32:06.390
and so you provide an orthotic for her.

603
00:32:06.390 --> 00:32:10.950
So we're just very briefly gonna go through these.

604
00:32:10.950 --> 00:32:13.590
You all have seen plantar fasciitis.

605
00:32:13.590 --> 00:32:14.910
Typically, they're tender

606
00:32:14.910 --> 00:32:17.490
right over the medial calcaneal tubercle.

607
00:32:17.490 --> 00:32:19.680
And it's the first steps in the morning

608
00:32:19.680 --> 00:32:23.010
or the first steps after I've had some prolonged rest,

609
00:32:23.010 --> 00:32:25.920
but I am actually tender.

610
00:32:25.920 --> 00:32:27.543
This patient wasn't tender.

611
00:32:29.055 --> 00:32:31.470
Your patients are gonna do lots of things.

612
00:32:31.470 --> 00:32:32.820
They're gonna ice and stretch

613
00:32:32.820 --> 00:32:34.740
and do a little bit of massage.

614
00:32:34.740 --> 00:32:36.600
You can give them a night splint,

615
00:32:36.600 --> 00:32:38.460
effective for up to three weeks.

616
00:32:38.460 --> 00:32:40.440
Really not effective beyond that.

617
00:32:40.440 --> 00:32:42.450
Or you can put them in orthotics,

618
00:32:42.450 --> 00:32:44.760
and it's over the counter orthotics.

619
00:32:44.760 --> 00:32:46.620
They have gotten so good,

620
00:32:46.620 --> 00:32:51.093
we just really don't use custom orthotics in general.

621
00:32:52.380 --> 00:32:54.240
And then Morton's neuroma,

622
00:32:54.240 --> 00:32:58.590
remember the entrapment of the intermetatarsal nerve.

623
00:32:58.590 --> 00:33:00.690
Third and fourth web space most common,

624
00:33:00.690 --> 00:33:02.730
women are more commonly affected.

625
00:33:02.730 --> 00:33:03.870
How do we treat it?

626
00:33:03.870 --> 00:33:06.723
A wide toe box, low heels,

627
00:33:07.590 --> 00:33:11.640
and consider possibly orthotics and/or an injection.

628
00:33:11.640 --> 00:33:13.260
And then tarsal tunnel syndrome,

629
00:33:13.260 --> 00:33:14.880
which is what this patient had,

630
00:33:14.880 --> 00:33:17.970
which is the great mimicker of plantar fasciitis.

631
00:33:17.970 --> 00:33:21.420
She had that medial heel pain, but no tenderness.

632
00:33:21.420 --> 00:33:25.410
If you are really gonna sort of decipher this,

633
00:33:25.410 --> 00:33:27.690
you might try doing Tine's test

634
00:33:27.690 --> 00:33:29.940
over the posterior tibial nerve

635
00:33:29.940 --> 00:33:34.920
to see if I can aggravate her symptoms through that.

636
00:33:34.920 --> 00:33:37.920
Okay, and that's it. Thank you very much.

637
00:33:37.920 --> 00:33:39.870
<v David>Thank you very much Dr. Gary.</v>

638
00:33:40.848 --> 00:33:43.431
(gentle music)

